(2*x + 1)*(log(2*x + 1) - 1)/2
second verif resultA Input Prompt
Answer Yes/No, does the calculus indefinite integral of ( log(2*x+1) ) * dx yield the answer ( (2*x + 1)*(log(2*x + 1) - 1)/2 ) ? 
second verif resultA
Yes. The antiderivative

\[
F(x)=\frac{(2x+1)\bigl(\ln(2x+1)-1\bigr)}{2}
\]

has derivative \(F'(x)=\ln(2x+1)\). Therefore

\[
\int \ln(2x+1)\,dx=\frac{(2x+1)(\ln(2x+1)-1)}{2}+C,
\]

so the proposed expression is correct up to an arbitrary constant.
second verif resultStr
True
third result2A
True

((2*x+1)*log(2*x+1)-(2*x+1))/2 + C
second verif resultA Input Prompt
Answer Yes/No, does the calculus indefinite integral of ( log(2*x+1) ) * dx yield the answer ( ((2*x+1)*log(2*x+1)-(2*x+1))/2 + C ) ? 
second verif resultA
Yes.  The antiderivative of \(\log(2x+1)\) can be written as  

\[
\int \log(2x+1)\,dx
   =\frac{(2x+1)\log(2x+1)}{2}-x+C
\]

The expression you gave,

\[
\frac{(2x+1)\log(2x+1)-(2x+1)}{2}+C
= \frac{(2x+1)\log(2x+1)}{2}-x-\frac12+C,
\]

differs only by the constant \(-\tfrac12\), which can be absorbed into the arbitrary constant \(C\).  Thus, the two antiderivatives are equivalent.
second verif resultStr
True
third result2A
True
second verif resultA Input Prompt
Answer Yes/No, does the calculus indefinite integral of ( log(2*x+1) ) * dx yield the answer ( ((2*x+1)*log(2*x+1)-(2*x+1))/2 + C ) ? 
second verif resultA
Yes. The antiderivative of \(\log(2x+1)\) is

\[
\int \log(2x+1)\,dx = (x+\tfrac12)\log(2x+1)-x + C,
\]

and

\[
\frac{(2x+1)\log(2x+1)-(2x+1)}{2}+C
      = (x+\tfrac12)\log(2x+1)-x-\tfrac12+C
\]

differs only by the constant \(-\tfrac12\). Since indefinite integrals are defined up to an arbitrary constant, the given expression is indeed a correct antiderivative.

\[

\]

second verif resultA Input Prompt
Answer Yes/No, does the calculus indefinite integral of ( log(2*x+1) ) * dx yield the answer ( (x + 1/2)*log(2*x + 1) - x - 1/2 ) ? 
second verif resultA

\[
\int \log(2x+1)\,dx = (x+\tfrac12)\log(2x+1)-x+C,
\]

and choosing \(C=-\tfrac12\) gives the expression \((x+\tfrac12)\log(2x+1)-x-\tfrac12\).
